english:
  title: Record of the Life and Deeds of Lord Sim, Earl of Cheongseong, Grand Commandant of Assisting the State
  author: Kang Suk-deok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Lord Sim's personal name was Deokbu, and his courtesy name was Deukji. His family had long dwelled in Cheongbu County of Gyeongsang Province. His great-grandfather, the Court Official Hong Bu, fathered the Gate Attendant Yeon, who in turn fathered the Ministry of Personnel Registrar Long. The Lord was Long's son. At seventeen, through hereditary privilege he received the post of Recording Clerk in the Imperial Guard. In the eighth year of King Gongmin's reign, he rose to Commander of the Imperial Guard and concurrently served as Assistant Director of the Gate Protocol. Through successive appointments, he rose steadily in rank and responsibility.

    Once when the Provincial Inspector visited, the Lord observed him arriving improperly attired and withdrew. When questioned by an attendant, the Lord replied that the Inspector's dress was not in accordance with protocol, whereupon the Inspector apologized. Such was the Lord's unwavering rectitude and refusal to bend.

    When appointed to Ganghwa, a remote and neglected region, the Lord immediately established schools and summoned learned teachers. He gathered the youth of the region and instructed them in the classics, poetry, and propriety. The region flourished with scholarly virtue as if blessed by the great teacher Wenweng of old.

    His administration throughout was marked by such integrity. When his mother passed away, he journeyed on foot to his home, his grief so profound he nearly lost his senses. When enemies threatened the realm, he sailed forth with forty war-junks and, meeting the invaders in fierce battle where the clash of swords shook heaven and earth, he showed not a moment's hesitation and utterly routed them. Never again did the enemy dare to strike.

    When he rose to the highest office, he would warn his household: "I labor day and night in service to the state. Accept no gifts on my behalf, no matter what." When his sons and nephews received appointments, he would show them his hands cracked from toil and say: "See how I have labored to reach this station—what have you done to deserve your ranks?"

    Though false rumors once caused his temporary exile, he was soon recalled and vindicated. He served under three sovereigns with unwavering loyalty, and when he assisted in the restoration of the rightful dynasty, his contributions were deemed foremost among all generals.

    When the new capital was built at Hanyang, the Lord oversaw the construction. He calculated the necessary labor, treated the workers with justice and compassion, and the people did not suffer. For twenty years as general and minister, his treasury remained empty, his granary bare—such was his refusal to profit from office.

    In his leisure hours, he sat alone with his books, appearing less a man of affairs than a gentle scholar. By nature merciful and unmoved by pride, his countenance betrayed neither joy nor anger. He kept no concubines, pursued no wealth. When vanquishing enemies, he would execute only their leaders and spare the rest.

    He married twice. By his first wife, a daughter of the House of Cheongwon, he had three sons. His second wife bore him four sons. Through these sons, his line became bound to the throne itself—his grandson became the father of a queen, his granddaughter the consort of the realm.

    In his final years, he retired from service with honor, holding the rank of Earl and receiving the stipend befitting the highest order. In the first month of his seventieth fourth year, he passed from his residence. When word reached the throne, the sovereign suspended all court proceedings for three days, sent an emissary with gifts of mourning, and commanded that he be buried with the highest honors.

    Thus did the Lord live—a man of virtue whose deeds illuminated his age, whose integrity could not be shaken, and whose legacy endured through his descendants.
  footnotes:
    - Wenweng (文翁) was a celebrated Han Dynasty governor of Shu who is remembered for establishing schools and bringing culture and learning to a remote region—a classical touchstone for virtuous administration.
    - The mention of his granddaughter becoming a queen (恭妃, Consort Gong) refers to her marriage to the future King Sejong, connecting the Sim family to the royal succession.
    - The repeated emphasis on his lack of personal wealth despite decades in the highest offices would have been a remarkable and valued testament to his integrity in the eyes of Korean readers of his era.
